      {
        "id": 4312114,
        "name": "Alan Rath",
        "username": "Alan_Rath",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/alan_rath/{size}/644_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-03-04T20:33:46.596Z",
        "cooked": "<p><a href=\"https://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=4422822&amp;iNote=11009601\"><b>2021 Daniel Bouland Morgon Les D\u00e9lys Vignes plant\u00e9es en 1926</b></a> - France, Burgundy, Beaujolais, Morgon (3/2/2024)<br>\nGood medium garnet color, decent depth of raspberry, cranberry, sour cherry fruit, on the slightly austere side, but not without flavor, earthy, dried leaves, slightly chalky, grippy tannins are present but not dominant. Really quite nice, with good interest, though a definite departure from recent more solar vintages. If this retains its fruit while it ages, it could be very nice in a few years.<br><br>Night 2: nose is showing some slight green vegetal notes, more than the first night; palate is unchanged, initially somewhat austere, until you accept it and adjust, then a bit more flavor emerges. Restrained, lean, sinewy, even austere. Only question is, does it evolve and blossom with age, or recede further and wither into nothing? <b>(88 points)</b></p>",
