      {
        "id": 4312537,
        "name": "Robert Alfert",
        "username": "Robert.A.Jr",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/robert.a.jr/{size}/76968_2.png",
        "created_at": "2024-03-05T12:37:39.804Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-Monopole_Cru\" data-username=\"Alan_Rath\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"319257\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/alan_rath/48/644_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Alan_Rath:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Everyone\u2019s tastes are different lol.  I\u2019ve found most 21 reds from both Burgundy and Beaujolais to be one the leaner side, sometimes too austere for me. But I\u2019m not fond of solar vintages, like 15 and 18. 19 is at the limit for me, and a lot of 20s have been too ripe. Guess I have a pretty narrow range lol. Have loved most 16s and 14s.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I\u2019m a fan of 2021.  I\u2019m betting this Bouland would be in my wheelhouse.  I love it but avoid the riper years like 18 and 15 as this wine pushes boundaries to me.  It\u2019s. Riper more powerful expression of Beaujolais, often even expressing Northern Rhone notes.</p>",
